## Voice and Writing Standards

These are non-negotiable. Every line of content we produce is checked against these.

**1. Sentence economy.** The thesis line is always short. No subordinate clauses on the claim. If the key idea needs a comma, rewrite it.
- Good: "AI implements now. Faster and more cheaply than any human ever will."
- Bad: "AI is now capable of implementing code faster and more cheaply than any human developer ever will be able to."

**2. The standalone sentence.** The sharpest sentence in a section stands alone as its own paragraph.
- "It made you a worse asker. And asking is most of the job."
- "More software is coming. Not less."

**3. The reframe pattern.** State the wrong assumption. Kill it in one line. State the truth.
- "YouTube didn't need more camera operators. It needed more storytellers."

**4. Concrete before abstract.** Open with the specific, grounded image. Then broaden.
- "Eighteen seconds. A man at a zoo." — then the industry insight.
- "A 3-person team built a complete banking platform in 6 months" — then the thesis.

**5. Data inside prose, never listed.** Statistics don't appear as bullet points. They live inside a sentence that gives them meaning.
- Good: "Writing new code: 16% of the week. The rest: debugging, understanding systems, communicating, deciding."
- Bad: "Developers spend 16% of their time coding, 35% on code management, 23% in meetings..."

**6. Present tense for truth.** State the claim in present tense. Not "will" or "could" — what is true now.

**7. No hedging.** No "perhaps", "might suggest", "it could be argued." State it plainly or don't state it.

**8. Payoff last.** Every section ends on its sharpest sentence. Not a transition. Not a soft summary. The last line is the one that stays.

**For email/newsletter specifically:**
- Subject line must be specific enough that the wrong reader self-selects out. Not "Why every solution fails the same way" (category) — instead: "They hired a new PPIC head three times. The delays didn't improve." (claim)
- If the case study is fictional or composited, say so upfront. Never present fictional evidence as fact.
- Close with a question the reader takes back to their business — not a CTA. Content earns attention before asking for anything.

